\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study of our genes has uncovered complex interactions of proteins that
 bind to the DNA in order to and regulate important patterns of gene expression.
 One type of protein that is important for gene regulation are transcription
 factors.
 Transcription factors are generally 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sequence specific
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which means that they tend to bind to a specific DNA sequence called a
 sequence “motif”.
 Their binding sites can affect nearby genes.
 Identifying transcription factor binding sites is important for understanding
 gene regulation, and recently, differences in genome regulation have been
 investigated by finding differences in transcription factor binding sites
 across different conditions or related species.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One method that is used to experimentally profile DNA protein interactions
 is called chromatin immunoprecipitation.
 Chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) uses a special antibody to target
 a protein and extract the bound DNA-protein complexes from a cell lysate.
 Afterwards, the proteins are unlinked from the DNA resulting in a DNA library
 that is enriched for the protein binding sites.
 Chromatin immunoprecipitation combined with high throughput sequencing
 (ChIP-seq) can be used to DNA sequencing technology which results in millions
 of short DNA reads (20-25bp) that correspond to the specific protein-DNA
 interaction that we are intersted in.
 ChIP-seq can be used to analyze the whole-genome transcription factor binding
 profile, but the methods for analysis have been limited by certain problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identifying transcription factor binding sites from the high throughput
 sequencing data essentially uses what is commonly known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peak finding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The transcription factor binding sites appear as peaks in the data, or
 more specifically, there is a significantly overrepresented coverage of
 a certain sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent studies have tried understand gene regulation by comparing different
 experiments across related species to determine how the binding sites vary.
 These studies have compared the transcription factor binding sites from
 mouse to human 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

, from different fly species, and different strains of yeast 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zheng_genetic_2010"

\end_inset

.
 The results show that transcription factor binding sites vary significantly
 between species, and even between related individuals.
 Between human and mouse, anywhere between 41-80% of binding sites for a
 particular transcritpion factor are not conserved
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

.
 Even between different individual strains of yeast, there is a high turnover
 of the transcription factor binding sites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zheng_genetic_2010"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, the metrics for identifying transcription factor binding
 sites, such as p-values and FDR, read depth, etc.
 are not directly comparable across different experiments, which leads to
 difficulties for comparing them.
 We created software for comparing ChIP-seq experiments and finding significant
 differential peaks using statistical testing.
 We used our algorithm show evidence for differential peaks that are called
 by peak callers across experiments.
\end_layout

