\begin_layout Subsection
Chromatin immunoprecipitation and ChIP-seq
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DNA-binding proteins have been extensively studied using chromatin immunoprecipi
tation (ChIP) which effectively creates a DNA library that is enriched for
 a particular DNA-binding protein of interest.
 ChIP experiments have been applied to many different experimental methods,
 including electrophoresis gels (ChIP-PCR), microarray hybridization (ChIP-chip)
, and high-throughput sequencing (ChIP-seq) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "collas_chromatin_2009"

\end_inset

.
 The scope of these studies has become larger in general to provide a whole-geno
me view of the transcription factor activity and to uncover the properties
 of gene regulatory systems including dynamics and evolutionary relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chromatin immunoprecipitation combined with high throughput sequencing (ChIP-seq
) is produces millions of short sequencing reads from DNA fragments that
 are associated with a particular DNA-protein interaction.
 To find transcription factor binding sites are identified, peak finding
 algorithms are commonly used to locate significantly number of reads covering
 a DNA sequence is significantly enriched.
 These peak-finding algorithms have become important for analyzing this
 data, but many peak finding algorithms only analyze ChIP-seq experiments
 individually, and few algorithms are developed for comparing across experiments.
 It is is especially problematic because the metrics that characterize the
 binding sites across different experiments are generally not directly comparabl
e.
 
\end_layout

