\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison of ChIP experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare the results of chromatin immunoprecipitation for transcription
 factor binding sites, a general assessment looks at the overlapping peaks
 (peak-centric approach) or the overlapping target-genes (gene-centric approach)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

.
 Using microarray technology, the gene-centric approach was important because
 the microarrays were printed with oligonucleotides corresponding to genes.
 This enabled microarray gene expression experiments to detect mRNA expression
 levels, and so a gene to gene comparison was a clear discriminator.
 Using chromatin immunoprecipitation microarrays (ChIP-chip) the microarrays
 would be printed with oligonucleotides upstream of the target genes in
 order to detect the transcription factors that are the most likely regulators.
 The peak-centric approach was first started using high-density oligonucleotide
 arrays 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

 which gives higher resolution and therefore allows detection of narrower
 transcription factor binding site peaks.
 Using the peak-centric approach, overlapping peaks can be detected directly,
 and the target gene is not necessarily inferred, which has advantages for
 comparing the sequence similarity.
 Nevertheless, both approaches have advantages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finding transcription factor binding sites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note: briefly explain why finding transcription factor binding sites reduces
 to peak calling)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We looked at a popular and open-source software package for peak finding
 -- MACS (Model-based analysis of ChIP-seq).
 Brief overview of the peak calling methodology is as follows: To find the
 potential binding sites from the data, MACS calculates the distribution
 of reads in the background that are not associated with any transcription
 factor binding.
 MACS uses a Poisson distribution to model the expected number of in the
 scanning window given the total number of reads and the whole genome size.
 Then peaks are identified as the likelihood of receiving a large number
 of reads in our scan window compared with the background.
 The resulting output is a list of high confidence ChIP-seq peaks that represent
 potential transcription factor binding sites.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the statistical problem that peak finders face is a classic
 problem: they must be sensitive enough to find significant instances, and
 avoid Type I errors, but it must also be discrimitive enough to avoid false
 positives, or Type II errors.
 MACS has been shown to have wide popularity and it shows a good ability
 to identify peaks.
 But the methods that have been used for comparing experiments have basically
 reduced to finding overlaps of peaks from individual experiments, and calling
 non-overlapping peaks unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identifying differences in transcription factor occupancy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note: this section needs more “structure” to get point across)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methods for identifying differences in ChIP-seq data have been demonstrated
 by comparing overlapping peaks.
 However, to go beyond overlapping peaks, and to identify differential peaks,
 the then instead of looking at the distribution of reads across the whole
 genome to find peaks, the distribution is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turned on its side
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 such that the read counts are compared across experiments at a specific
 genome position.
 This leads to a problem where we have a small n (number of experiments)
 but a large p (number of tests) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit_statistics_2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach for doing a differential analysis using MACS is to use one
 ChIP-seq experiment as control and another ChIP-seq as the compared set.
 Then, differences in the peaks are found when the dynamic Poisson background
 is low (not a peak in the control) and the read rate is high in the compared
 set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To incorporate replicates into this analysis, reads can also be pooled simply
 by concatenating read files.
 Pooling replicate experiments into MACS might be useful to increase saturation,
 but it does not help solve the small n, large p problem, so it is unusual
 for an experimental design point of view.
 Replicates have been shown to be important in measuring differential expression
 in microarray data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit_statistics_2004"

\end_inset

, and so we considered methods that are similar that would help us find
 differential peaks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another method for comparing experiments to find conserved binding sites
 is MANorm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shao_manorm:_2012"

\end_inset

 which uses a linear model to correct for bias that may exist for differences
 in the reads from overlapping peaks across different experiments .
 MANorm uses the overlapping peaks called on individual experiments from
 a peak caller such as MACS as inputs and then normalizes all reads by the
 linear model.
 Then, the peak calls are adjusted using a Bayesian Poisson.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A method for comparing ChIP-seq experiments directly using log-ratios is
 DIME.
 DIME uses a LOESS (locally weighted scatterplot smoothing) normalization
 which has been applied to other normalizations such as DIME 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taslim_comparative_2009"

\end_inset

.
 Then it finds differential peaks according to maximum likelihood expectation
 from a mixture model of K-Normal and Exponential (GNG) or NUDGE (Normal-Uniform
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We looked at these options and also apply the moderated t-test for finding
 differential peaks from the limma 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "smyth_linear_2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

