\begin_layout Subsection
Considerations - assumption of normal distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the assumption of the underlying distribution being normal assumption
 is common and useful, sequencing data is discrete and many algorithms have
 considered these discrete probability distributions.
 For identifying peaks, Poisson is shown to be effective by the MACS algorithm
 by mdoelling the distribution of reads across the genome.
 For comparing experiments, the distribution is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turned on its side
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 That is to say that the distribution of read counts compare across all
 experiments for a specific genome position.
 We employ a moderated t-test that show promising results.
 Other frameworks that have been applied to sequencing data include edgeR
 which has similar design principles as limma but it uses a discrete negative
 binomial distribution that can accomodate the different variances from
 comparing across experiments.
\end_layout

